[2]
Date: 12 Jul 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Financial Times, 10 Jul 2002 [edited]
<http://news.ft.com/servlet/ContentServer?pagename=FT.com/StoryFT/FullStory&c=StoryFT&cid=1026311886003&p=1012571727166>

EU takes action over food scare
-------------------------------
The European Union agreed on Wed 10 Jul 2002 to step up efforts to deal
with the latest food scare to rock the continent.
The EU's leading food safety committee heard reports from the Dutch,
Belgian, and Irish authorities on moves to trace the source of
contamination by medroxyprogesterone-acetate (MPA), a hormone used in the
human contraceptive pill, which is believed to have affected meat, animal
feed and possibly soft drinks.
The Standing Committee for the Food Chain and Animal Health met in special
session after the Belgian food safety agency announced this week it had
found traces of the banned hormone in materials supplied to two soft drink
producers by Bioland, a now-bankrupt Belgian company suspected of being
behind the scandal.
The Netherlands has agreed to block farms and feed producers potentially
affected by the contamination and to report on the results of test being
carried out. All other member states undertook to trace potentially
affected food or feed and to discover if companies on their territory were
customers of Bioland. They also agreed to verify whether pharmaceutical
waste, the likely cause of the contamination, was being correctly disposed of.
A scandal over the contamination of animal feed with dioxin - a highly
toxic chemical - was a significant factor in the downfall of the last
Belgian government and led to the tightening of EU feed regulations.
[Byline: Michael Mann]
