[3]
Date: 12 Jul 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: De Telegraaf, Amsterdam 11 Jul 2002 [translated, edited]
<http://www.telegraaf.nl/nieuwslink/teksten/nws.nederlandse.nederland.html>

Brinkhorst, European penalty is a fable
----------------------------------------
Brussels/The Hague: Minister Brinkhorst of Agriculture has placed 2 new
farms under supervision because they have received suspect feed. The member
of the government contradicted on Wednesday remarks from Belgium to the
effect that 65 Dutch cattle farms and 300 pig and poultry farms would be
blockaded upon the direction of European veterinary experts.
"We have explained in Brussels what we have done the previous week. That we
have received the penalty from Europe is a fairy tale," said Brinkhorst
Wednesday night. The minister expects that the now in total 55 farms placed
under supervision can resume their activities in about a week.
The directorate of Belgian Federal Agency for the Safety of the Food Chain
(FAVV) has caused a tumult by announcing the blockade of the Dutch farms.
European veterinary experts supposedly did this to prevent the prohibited
hormone MPA from ending up in the human food chain.
According to the FAVV Director, P. Vanthemsche, the contamination in
Holland seems to be more extensive than initially estimated. Brinkhorst
contradicts this. Vanthemsche said that Holland should provide its review
of the situation on all the blockaded farms the latest by Thursday morning,
so that the other EU member states can adopt their own preventive measures.
The member states have been guided to carry out extensive investigations in
their own countries as to whether similar cases have taken place.
According to FAVV, the source of the contamination is the IRISH company
Cara Environmental, that -- without informing the authorities-- has been
exporting, since 1995, medical waste contaminated with the pregnancy
hormone MPA. Cara has exported the product to, amongst others, Bioland in
the Belgian area of Arendonk, which manufactures glucose syrup. Bioland,
owned by 2 Dutch brothers, mixed the contaminated glucose syrup into animal
feed and exported that subsequently to Holland.
The soft drink industry is also burdened by the affair. Bioland delivered
glucose syrup also to soft drink producers. According to Vanthempsche, the
contaminated glucose syrup has supposedly been found, in the interim, at 4
soft drink factories, 2 in Belgium, 1 in Germany and 1 in Holland. In
Belgium, it is presumed that only the small west Flemish lemonade producer
Puck has received it. The name of the Dutch producer has not been revealed
yet. According to the Dutch authorities, MPA is not harmful to public health.
